Final_commuting

2024-05-07

Introduction

This document seeks to answer the inference question:

What drives commuting decisions?

The goal of this investiagtion therefore is to determine which variables are the strongest predictors of commuting patterns.

This is done in a few ways:

  • firstly, by joining the commuting data with point geometries, the spatial variation in some key variables is established.
  • Secondly, the variables are then investigated for pairwise and multi-collinearity. This offers important context for when evaluating model results and variable importances.
  • Thirdly, to disseminate variable importances for different amounts of commuting, linear models were trained for each journey_count_decile, so that the most important variables at each level could be compared. Note, given the non-linear and high dimensional structure of the data, linear models were not expected to perform well; they serve only as an indicator of the most influential variables for different commuting levels.
  • The variable importances by deciles were then compared to variable importances calculated using a random forest model. A random forest model was expected to perform well with this data for the same reason a linear model would perform poorly: the nonlinear data requires a flexible model and the high dimensionality suits a random forest better than alternative models such as KNN as they can only measure distance which would have required the normalisation of all the variables and still would not have returned useful insights on variable importances.
  • Following this, a random forest model was tuned for minimal predictive error to reassess variable importances. The variable importances returned from this model with reduced error and improved accuracy are more reliable. The variable importances returned from a poorly performing linear model will be less useful - for example a variable being unimportant in a linear might indicate it its influence is non-linear, not that it neccisarily does not influence the outcomes.
  • Using these variables, an XGBoost model was trained. This model type trains considerably faster than Random Forest models and also handles high dimensional non linear data. Its variable importances therefore offer useful validation for the variable importances from the Random Forest model.
  • All of these investigations contribute to painting a picture of what drives commuting decisions.
  • Finally, there is some speculation as how the answers for this question could be more accurate and robust but were made impossible by the computational constraints.

All of the displayed variables clearly differ spatially.

  • journey_score shows an interesting patter where points further away from others appear to have higher journey scores - this could be because these areas have fewer local neighbours and therefore the people there have fewer accessible commuting options.
  • population origin should be approximately equal since the LADs are meant to be represenative of population size.
  • gcse_rate_origin shows a complicated spatial pattern. This score is often used as part of deprivation indicies and therefore could be a proxy for LAD affluence.
  • life_satisfaction_origin also shows a complicated spatial pattern. The lowest scores appear to be in the centre of urban areas however this could be closely tied to age demographics. Fore example, those of retirment age or those with financial stability are likely to have higher life satisfcation than young people with financial instability.
  • housing_growth_origin appears to have a similar pattern to population_origin. A parwise correlation measure may confirm this.
  • employment_rate has an interesting spatial pattern where there appears to be an approximate north south divide, where the north has higher rates of unemployment. This could be a consequence, among other things, of people moving from the north to London for higher salaries. This is speculative, and the answering of such a question is beyond the cope of this investigation.

Interestingly, population_origin and housing_growth_origin show pairwise correlation (0.64) which would explain the spatial variance detected earlier in population_origin. - These areas have seen greater (or worse) popluation growth since the LAD boundaries were set than is average. Note, correlation is not equivalent to causation however this seems a likely explanation. (the same is true with population_dest and housing_growth_dest).

travel_time_origin and travel_time_destination do have positive pairwise correlation (0.65) although this is actually lower than I would have expected. These two variables seem intrinsically tied together so for them to only have a 0.65 pairwise correlation seems unusual. Future studies might look at why this is and whether travel time discrepancies in the time of day for travel can have such a big impact or if there is another explanation or even if there is an error in the data.

distance was negatively correlated (-0.6) with journey_count_decile. Indicating that for further distances, less people make the journey which is expected. I might have expected this correlation to be even higher at least for middle and further journeys.

value_added_hourly_origin and travel_time_origin show some positive correlation (0.49) and could indicate people are willing to travel further for higher salaries. This could also be that people are able to afford to live in suburbs and commute.

Surprisingly, travel_time_origin and travel_time_dest are not strongly correlated with distance (0.21, 0.33 respectively). This could be because distance has been done with euclidean distance however if this were the case we would expect travel time to be more important than distance in the modelling.

# selecting variables to include
all_vars <- names(commute_gdf_numeric)

# excluding unwanted variables
excluded_vars <- c("journey_score", 
                   "...1", 
                   "journey_count_decile",
                   "area_name_origin", 
                   "area_code_origin", 
                   "area_name_dest", 
                   "area_code_dest",

vars_to_include <- all_vars[!all_vars %in% excluded_vars]

# checking how many variables
length(vars_to_include)
## [1] 15
# writing forumla as string
formula_string <- paste("journey_score~", paste(vars_to_include, collapse = " + "))

# Converting to formula
formula <- as.formula(formula_string)
# running seperate linear models by journey_count_decile (highly correlated with journey_score (0.82))
model_results <- commute_gdf_numeric %>% 
  group_by(journey_count_decile) %>%
  nest() %>%
  mutate(
    lm_model = map(data, ~ lm(formula, data = .)),
    lm_summary = map(lm_model, summary),
    vif_values = map(lm_model, ~ vif(.))
  )

# Getting variable importances
var_importances <- model_results %>%
  mutate(
    var_importance = map(lm_model, ~ varImp(.)),  # Ensure varImp is from the correct package
    var_importance_summary = map(var_importance, ~ as.data.frame(.) %>%
                                   rownames_to_column() %>%
                                   arrange(desc(Overall)) %>%
                                   select(variable = rowname, importance = Overall))
  )

# Getting VIFs
vif_results <- var_importances %>%
  mutate(
    vif = map(lm_model, ~ vif(.))
  )

# putting into a data frame for printing
vif_df <- bind_rows(lapply(vif_results$vif, as.data.frame), .id = "Model_Number")
names(vif_df) <- c("variable", "importance")
# printing kable for vif
kable(
  vif_df

Also of ionterest is that the other most important variables are not the same. For example, if it were always distance or value_added_hourly_dest then I might say these were the two most important variables but as it stands the model results indicate the most important variables (other than distance) are highly dependent on which decile ofjourney count is being modelled.

# setting training controls 

train_control <- trainControl(
  method = "boot",          # bootstrapping
  number = 10,             # number of resamples
  allowParallel = TRUE
)

# setting train controls
nested_train_control <- trainControl(
  method = "cv",          # using cross validation
  number = 5,             # number of folds
  allowParallel = TRUE
)
# setting training formula

all_vars <- names(commute_gdf_numeric)

excluded_vars <- c("journey_score", "journey_count_decile", "is_local_commute")

vars_to_include <- all_vars[!all_vars %in% excluded_vars]
length(vars_to_include)
## [1] 15
# writing forumla as string
formula_string <- paste("journey_score~", paste(vars_to_include, collapse = " + "))

# Converting to formula
formula <- as.formula(formula_string)
# training random forest model

set.seed(123)

rf_model <- train(
    formula,
  data = commute_gdf_numeric,
  method = "rf",            # Random forest
  metric = "RMSE",          # Optimising for RMSE (root mean squared error)

  search_control = nested_train_control, # nested cross validation control
  allowParallel = TRUE
)

The error of the XGBoost model is slightly lower than the random forest model (MSE=0.374 vs 0.344) and its R2 is lower (0.336 vs 0.383). Ultimately these model performed similarly. The reduced error of the XGBoost model indicates its variable importance findings might be more reliable however the difference is slight.

The XGBoost model orders the variable importances similarly to the random forest model (top three are in the same order) however the proportial importances differ: in the random forest model distance has a greater importnce than in XGBoost. Notably, the 4th and 5th most important variables for the XGBoost model are housing_growth_origin and value_added_hourly_dest whereas in the random forest model the 4th and 5th most important variables are population_origin and population_dest. This represents a significant divergence in the model outcomes.

I do not expect an ordinary GWR model to perform well with this data because it is constructed with linear models. A GWR model could be trained on this data to investigate the findings however:

Given the inherent spatial component to this question, and the high dimensionality and non linear behaviour of many of the variables I believe a geographically weighted random forest would perform best.

Below is some of the code I would use to train such a model. Variables were selected from a non-geographically weighted random forest model. Unfortunately, even when looking at a single day of the dataset and reducing features such as the number of trees and adjusting minimum leaf size this model did not finish training when left for 40 hours. The commented out code below has been left for interest but clearly this model style is not appropriate for the question given the available resources.

# looking for optimal bandwidth for geographically weighted random forest
# doing this by running large steps and repeating with incrementally smaller steps within appropriate range
# this approach saves computation compared to exhaustively stepping though all bandwidths. 

# set.seed(123)

# bandwidth calculation (done with different steps and ranges)
# grfbw = grf.bw(journey_score  ~
#        distance +
#        population_origin +
#        value_added_hourly_origin +
#        housing_growth_origin +
#        value_added_hourly_dest +
#        travel_time_dest +
#        gcse_rate_dest,
#        dataset = grf_dat,
#        kernel="adaptive", #  can also be "fixed"
#        coords = grf_dat[,  c("latitude", "longitude")],
#        bw.min = 10,
#        bw.max = 200,
#        step = 90,
#        trees=30, # set so low for finding the bandwidth
#        mtry=NULL, # default is 1/3 of variables
#        importance="impurity",
#        forests = FALSE,

Conclusions

Distance was the most important variable driving commuter decisions. While this may have been an expected outcome, I find it surprising that travel time was not the most important variable I would have only expected distance to represent a proxy measure for travel time.

Depending on the model for the order: housing_growth_origin, value_added_hourly_dest, emp_rate_dest, population_origin, and population_dest were in the top ten most important variables for both the XGBoost and the random forest models. For that reason, these and distance are the most important drivers of commuting decisons in the UK.

Limitations and Future Work

While distance was the most important variable, the way it is constructed is not perfect. This is because, to preserve anonimity, people are aggregated into LADs so anyone commuting inside their LAD is recorded to have travelled 0 metres. In contrast, someone going a potentially smaller distance between London LADs would have a non-zero distance travelled.

The aggregation of all variables into LADs is an issue. Higher spatial resolution would likely improve model outcomes because the currently resolution is likely masking many spatial patterns and inequalities.

Further work could involve cluster detection to organically detect urban clusters. For each cluster a separate random forest or XGBoost model could be trained to gain a spatially specific understanding of commuter decisions. This could only be done to supplement understandings derived from total models as this breaks the networks and would omit all data points for longer journeys. The merit of this approach over a spatially weighted rnaodm forest would be the reduced computation demands. By subsetting the data spatially there is some accommodation for spatial variance. Other subsets could be made such as North - South, London - Not London, etc.

Furthermore, the addition of demographic data per location should be investigated in future work. Especially age demographics may prove important in the prediction of commuting behaviour. For example, the weekday - weekend variation in the behaviour of 70+ will likely differ to younger demographics due to retirement.

Note, this investigation only examined a single day (2nd September 2019) however if this investigation were to be applied at different scales the variable importance of date and its derivable features would likely differ. For examples:

  • if looking at a single week this could be split into days of the week.
  • if looking at a month this could be split into weekend and not_weekend.
  • if looking at a year additional features such as school_holiday and bank_holiday might prove useful.
  • if this investigation looked at multiple years then features such as covid_lockdown would likely be be required.

Future work might consider retrying the geographically weighted random forest model with more computation or time available. Alternatively, a geographically weighted XGBoost model would train faster and could therefore represent a viable option. Both of these options would still be very computationally demanding and do not lend themselves to the entire data set without access to a powerful computer or a long time to allow model training.
